      <h1>Collaborative CAD Research Using Onshape</h1>
      <p>
        This research project investigated collaborative computer-aided design (CAD) workflows using 
        <strong>Onshape</strong>, a cloud-native CAD platform. The goal was to explore whether real-time collaboration in shared environments 
        can improve design efficiency, team communication, and the educational value of modeling.
      </p>

      <h2>Project Background</h2>
      <p>
        Traditional CAD tools like SolidWorks and NX are file-based and single-user focused, requiring manual version 
        management. In contrast, Onshape offers cloud-native features like document history, branching, and live editing. 
        Our team tested these features in a semester-long research study, comparing collaborative modeling outcomes with 
        individual workflows.
      </p>
      <p>
        This research was done with four student researchers in collaboration with a representative from Onshape as well as Professor Greg Jensen and Professor Jason Elliot.
      </p>

      <h2>Research Objectives</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Simulate industry-style collaborative CAD workflows using Onshape</li>
        <li>Measure differences in efficiency, speed, and part quality across workflows</li>
        <li>Identify useful features and limitations of browser-based modeling</li>
        <li>Gain hands-on experience with multi-user Part Studios and shared assemblies</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Learning Onshape | Setup & Team Structure</h2>
      <p>
        The team was divided into pairs working on a shared mechanical system: the <strong>Panther Pup Engine</strong>. 
        Each person focused on different subcomponents while collaborating in real time. Communication was done through 
        Onshape comments, live chat, and periodic meetings. The teams made sure to model together as much as possible, to ensure the "collaborative experience" was fully captured.
      </p>
