      <h2>Case Study: Grinder Vise Model-Off</h2>
      <p>
        To measure time savings, the team held a "model-off" challenge. The same part, a <strong>grinder vise</strong>, 
        was modeled by an individual and then collaboratively. Both versions were compared for time, accuracy, and workflow breakdown.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Individual time:</strong> ~6 hours total (including planning and constraints)</li>
        <li><strong>Team time:</strong> ~2.5 hours (3 people modeling simultaneously)</li>
        <li><strong>Outcome:</strong> Time cut by 59%, with similar model quality</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        The collaborative team finished faster by dividing the part into discrete features, modeling them in parallel, 
        and combining sketches in a shared studio. However, the total person-hours were slightly higher (~7.5 hours) 
        than solo modeling.
      </p>

      <figure>
        <img src="/images/grinder.png" alt="Model-Off Comparison" />
        <figcaption>Grinder Vise - Comparison of individual vs collaborative modeling workflow</figcaption>
      </figure>
      <p>
        This shows that time can be reduced when multiple people work on the part, effectively meaning that collaboration can cut down on design hours, but is less effective when it comes to labor hours. This is mainly due to the stepping on each other's feet that occurs when working on something as a team. But many things can be done to try and make workflow as efficient as possible, like planning beforehand and good communication.
      </p>

      <h2>Final Sprint: Panther Pup v2 Speedrun</h2>
<p>
  As a final challenge to wrap up the research, our team decided to recreate the Panther Pup Engine from scratch - but this time with speed and confidence. 
  Having already built the model once, we treated this second version as a <strong>modeling speedrun</strong>: how quickly could we recreate the essential structure using streamlined workflows?
</p>

<p>
  With better familiarity and tool awareness, the team completed the entire model in significantly less time. The second build emphasized part simplification, cleaner sketches, and minimal use of constraints where possible. 
  This exercise reinforced how much more efficiently collaborative modeling can work when roles are clear and tools are mastered.
</p>

