      <h2>Challenges & Limitations</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Drawings are single-user only (no live collab editing)</li>
        <li>Large assemblies lag on low-bandwidth internet</li>
        <li>Missing legacy features like origin axes in Part Studios</li>
        <li>Some users unfamiliar with version control concepts like branching</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        While Onshape has many benefits, learning curve and browser performance were sometimes limiting. Collaboration 
        required planning, shared naming conventions, and frequent syncing between team members.
      </p>

      <h2>Reflection</h2>
      <p>
        Overall, Onshape enabled fast prototyping and intuitive teamwork. The versioning system made it easy to explore 
        ideas without overwriting each other's work, and the real-time updates made group sessions productive. 
        Working in this cloud-native system felt closer to modern software development than traditional CAD modeling.
      </p>
      <p>
        CAD and modeling in general has been an individual task in industry and collaboration in CAD is the next step. Just like many other software that has become more cloud-based like Microsoft products as well as Google products, collaborative CAD has many use cases and can be effective when used efficiently. Learning to model collaboratively is crucial if and when industry starts shifting to collaborative systems like Onshape, like Garmin, Formlabs, and IBM already have.
      </p>
